into French law for the first time. The decree was the culmination of a decades-long effort to resolve the “métis question”: the educational, social, and civil issues surrounding the mixed population. Operating at the intersection of history, anthropology, and law, Empire’s Children reveals the unacknowledged but central role of race in the definition of French nationality. Through extensive archival work in both France and Vietnam, and a close reading of primary and secondary material from the Pacific islands and sub-Saharan and North Africa, Saada has created in Empire’s Children an original and compelling perspective on colonialism, law, race, and culture from the end of the nineteenth century until decolonization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCitizenshipxColoniesxHistoryxFrance. 0aCitizenshipzFrancexColoniesxHistory. 0aMiscegenationxColoniesxHistoryxFrance. 0aMiscegenationxColonieszFrancexHistory. 0aMiscegenationzFrancexColoniesxHistory. 0aRacially mixed peoplexColoniesxHistoryxFrance. 0aRacially mixed peoplexColonieszFrancexHistory. 0aRacially mixed peoplexLegal status, laws, etcxColoniesxHistoryxFrance. 0aRacially mixed peoplexLegal status, laws, etcxColonieszFrancexHistory. 0aRacially mixed peoplexLegal status, laws, etc.zFrancexColoniesxHistory. 0aRacially mixed peoplezFrancexColoniesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  arace, citizenship, colonies, france, french indochina, metis, interracial, mixed-race, parentage, vietnam, classification, empire, imperialism, colonialism, sexuality, law, history, anthropology, nationality, africa, pacific islands, paternity, identity, illegitimacy, abandonment, children, native, subjects, state power, colonial rule, nonfiction, filiation, family, orphanages, categorization, repatriation, decolonization.1 aGo